37:49.067 --> 37:56.040 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
But, Angela Kocherga, Walter
Cronkite School
of Journalism at Arizona State
University,

37:56.074 --> 37:58.343 align:left position:12.5%,start line:93.33% size:87.5%
thank you so much.

37:58.376 --> 38:02.614 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
ANGELA KOCHERGA: Thank you.

38:02.647 --> 38:09.053 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
JUDY WOODRUFF: Next: concussions
in football
and the college game.

38:09.087 --> 38:13.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Fans are increasingly aware of
concussions
at the pro level. The most
recent example

38:13.558 --> 38:18.997 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
was on Saturday, when Antonio
Brown of the
Pittsburgh Steelers suffered one
after a brutal

38:19.030 --> 38:24.903 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
hit by Cincinnati linebacker
Vontaze Burfict.
Burfict could be facing
suspension.

38:24.936 --> 38:30.475 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Tonight, tens of millions of
viewers will
watch Clemson and Alabama face
off in college

38:30.508 --> 38:35.980 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
football's championship game.
It's a big night
for the sport. But, like pro
football, one

38:36.014 --> 38:41.052 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
question lingering throughout
the season is
how teams are handling
concussions.

38:41.085 --> 38:46.257 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Hari Sreenivasan has one look at
that in a
conversation he recorded
earlier.

38:46.291 --> 38:51.396 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
Just as the NFL has taken new
steps to protect
players, some schools and teams
and the NCAA

38:51.429 --> 38:56.201 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
have taken new precautions as
well. But when
it comes to college football,
schools have

38:56.234 --> 39:01.139 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
more latitude on some decisions
and there
are questions about where a team
may take

39:01.172 --> 39:02.807 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
too big a risk.

39:02.840 --> 39:07.011 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
STAT, an online news site that
focuses on
health, medical and science, has
a report

39:07.045 --> 39:12.517 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
exploring whether some players
with too many
concussions are still allowed to
play.

39:12.550 --> 39:17.889 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
It tells it through the story of
a sophomore
quarterback, A.J. Long, who
played for Syracuse.

39:17.922 --> 39:23.027 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
After he suffered his third
concussion, the
team's head doctor summoned him.
He was told

39:23.061 --> 39:28.566 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
him he could no longer play at
Syracuse, but
A.J. wanted to keep playing
somehow.

39:28.600 --> 39:32.337 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
Here's an excerpt from a video
by STAT featuring
A.J. and his father.

39:32.370 --> 39:34.973 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A.J. LONG, Former Syracuse
Football Player:
He was like, hey, from my
professional opinion,

39:35.006 --> 39:40.044 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I think that it would be best if
you didn't
play football anymore, so,
therefore, I'm

39:40.078 --> 39:44.816 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
going to disqualify you from
continuing to
play contact sports at Syracuse
University.

39:44.849 --> 39:51.623 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
When you hear those words, and
it's the final
verdict, it hurts and it shocks
you.

39:51.656 --> 39:57.495 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ACE LONG, Father of A.J. Long:
When the doctor
called, he was really vague.
Well, when you're

39:57.528 --> 40:02.600 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
telling me that you're ending my
son's career,
you're worried about his
welfare, what is

40:02.634 --> 40:04.769 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this going to entail for the
rest of his life?

40:04.802 --> 40:09.173 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
A.J. LONG: After my family doing
their research
and telling me that we're going
to go to a

40:09.207 --> 40:12.577 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
specialist and we're going to
have them look
at it to tell us what they
think, because

40:12.610 --> 40:16.914 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
this is what they do for living,
what I'm
hoping happens is that they look
at my brain

40:16.948 --> 40:19.784 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and they tell me my brain is
fine and it's
completely safe for me to
continue to play

40:19.817 --> 40:21.686 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
the game that I love, in
football.

40:21.719 --> 40:26.124 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
ACE LONG: The brain is something
that you
can't play with, but, you know,
it's hard

40:26.157 --> 40:28.226 align:left position:12.5%,start line:86.67% size:87.5%
to put a value on the
competitive spirit.

40:28.259 --> 40:32.964 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
HARI SREENIVASAN: David
Armstrong is a reporter
for STAT and joins me now from
Boston.

40:32.997 --> 40:36.734 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
David, as you point out, and the
pictures
do in the piece, this is a kid
that has Syracuse

40:36.768 --> 40:40.772 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tattooed on his arm. He dreams
of playing
there. He wants it. You can tell
even from

40:40.805 --> 40:43.041 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
this video that he wants to play
ball.

40:43.074 --> 40:48.046 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
But the idea that he's
essentially now a free
agent and can be signed again by
another college,

40:48.079 --> 40:50.315 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
even after he has this history
of concussions.

40:50.348 --> 40:55.386 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG, STAT: Yes.
That's what was
really surprising to us, was
that a doctor

40:55.420 --> 41:01.993 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at one university thought that
his condition
was so perilous, and the danger
so extreme,

41:02.026 --> 41:07.098 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
that he could never play contact
sports again
at that university is then able
to go out

41:07.131 --> 41:13.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and be recruited by other
schools, and there
is no NCAA regulation or
restriction on that.

41:13.538 --> 41:17.942 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
So he is basically a free agent
now, with
several schools wooing him.

41:17.975 --> 41:22.947 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And how about
the tracking
on this? Is there any system
inside the NCAA?

41:22.980 --> 41:26.851 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
You talked to a lot of different
colleges
and sought information from so
many different

41:26.884 --> 41:30.888 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
schools. How do they know if
they're inheriting
an injured player?

41:30.922 --> 41:35.360 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Well, there is
no real way
to know for sure.

41:35.393 --> 41:39.764 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
The player might let them know
or they might
get some information from
someone they know

41:39.797 --> 41:46.337 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
at another school, but the NCAA
doesn't keep
a list or a database of players
who are medically

41:46.371 --> 41:51.609 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
disqualified. And what we found
was that we
approached the 65 schools that
are at the

41:51.642 --> 41:56.180 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
upper echelon of college
football, and we
asked all of them for basic
information about

41:56.214 --> 41:59.917 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
how many athletes are being
qualified for
concussions.

41:59.951 --> 42:05.490 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
And only nine even responded to
us. And two
gave us the information we were
looking for.

42:05.523 --> 42:09.594 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So it's clearly a subject
they're not comfortable
speaking about. And at the
moment, there is

42:09.627 --> 42:15.066 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
no real good solution that is
even being discussed
about how to make sure athletes
are being

42:15.099 --> 42:16.968 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
protected for the long term.

42:17.001 --> 42:20.872 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: Now, you point
out that
there isn't any single standard
on exactly

42:20.905 --> 42:22.907 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
how many concussions is too
many.

42:22.940 --> 42:24.742 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: That's true.

42:24.776 --> 42:27.945 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
We talked to -- one of the more
interesting
people, I think, in the story is
the University

42:27.979 --> 42:32.850 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
of Arizona head trainer. And he
told us that
he has disqualified a football
player for

42:32.884 --> 42:37.855 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
a single concussion because it
was so severe,
but that, in another case, he
had a player

42:37.889 --> 42:42.894 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with 10 concussions throughout
his college
career and his high school
career that he

42:42.927 --> 42:48.366 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
allowed to continue playing
because he didn't
think that the concussions were
so severe

42:48.399 --> 42:53.304 align:left position:12.5%,start line:73.33% size:87.5%
as to disable him and to
incapacitate him
and disqualify him from the
team.

42:53.337 --> 42:59.210 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: It almost
seems like the
player or the parents or the
family, their

42:59.243 --> 43:05.650 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
dreams are their own worst
enemy. Here's a
student who knows what the
potential outcomes

43:05.683 --> 43:09.253 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
are, at least with all the news
that we have
been seeing about what happens
to NFL players

43:09.287 --> 43:14.158 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
with CTE later in their career,
some of them
who have suffered concussions on
the gridiron.

43:14.192 --> 43:16.527 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Well, that's
right.

43:16.561 --> 43:21.299 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
I mean, part of the problem here
is the science
and research into this issue is
still in its

43:21.332 --> 43:26.137 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
infancy, and there is no real
good guidelines
on, for instance, how many
concussions are

43:26.170 --> 43:33.010 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
too many. So, you have A.J. Long
and his family,
who have two diametrically
opposed opinions,

43:33.044 --> 43:37.815 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
one from a doctor at Syracuse
who says, this
is too dangerous, you are not
playing anymore,

43:37.849 --> 43:42.286 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
and then another one from a
concussion center
in Philadelphia, a very
reputable one, that

43:42.320 --> 43:46.324 align:left position:0%,start line:80% size:100%
says, as of today, you are
cleared to play
full-contact football.

43:46.357 --> 43:53.431 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, you can imagine the angst
over a decision
like that, when you have black
and white decisions

43:53.464 --> 43:55.199 align:left position:0%,start line:93.33% size:100%
in front of you and evaluations.

43:55.233 --> 43:59.504 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: And those
decisions will
impact the rest of your, not
just playing

43:59.537 --> 44:03.875 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
career, but, if you have a pro
career, perhaps
the rest of your financial life
as well.

44:03.908 --> 44:08.880 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: Right, because
we know that,
in many cases, there are
long-term effects

44:08.913 --> 44:10.681 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
from these repeated blows to the
head.

44:10.715 --> 44:15.586 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So that's a calculation that the
family and
the player have to make. But
they're doing

44:15.620 --> 44:20.525 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
so with information that's very
confusing
to them and in a system where
one school can

44:20.558 --> 44:25.096 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
tell you, you can't play because
it's too
dangerous, and another school
says, come and

44:25.129 --> 44:26.998 align:left position:25%,start line:93.33% size:75%
play for us.

44:27.031 --> 44:31.102 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
So, that's why we want to
chronicle this story
and A.J.'s decision, because a
lot of athletes

44:31.135 --> 44:32.904 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
are finding themselves in this
position.

44:32.937 --> 44:36.407 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
HARI SREENIVASAN: What was the
reason that
the schools gave you when they
didn't give

44:36.440 --> 44:38.242 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
you the information you were
looking for?

44:38.276 --> 44:43.748 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
DAVID ARMSTRONG: They mostly
cited privacy
concerns, even though we didn't
ask for names

44:43.781 --> 44:46.551 align:left position:0%,start line:86.67% size:100%
or identifying information of
that nature.

44:46.584 --> 44:52.023 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
They said that we would be to,
in some cases,
figure out who the injured
athlete is, and,

44:52.056 --> 44:56.794 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
therefore, that's a violation of
federal law
protecting student privacy and
also health

44:56.827 --> 44:58.696 align:left position:37.5%,start line:93.33% size:62.5%
records.

44:58.729 --> 45:01.632 align:left position:0%,start line:73.33% size:100%
In a lot of cases, we don't
